The paper deals with understanding the incentives provided by algorithmic decision-makers, which is a problem in the field of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The authors also discuss the limitations of classical methods for interpreting the behavior of non-linear models, which is a topic in the field of cryptography and security (cs.CR). The paper also proposes a mathematical framework for understanding algorithmic incentives, which involves modeling the problem as a Markov Decision Process (MDP), which is a topic in the field of control and optimization (cs.CY) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the authors demonstrate the utility of their method by applying it to two real-world settings, which involves practical applications of machine learning and optimization (cs.SI).
